text: Mechanistic Insights into the Oxidative Rearrangement Catalyzed by the Unprecedented Dioxygenase ChaP Involved in Chartreusin Biosynthesis Xinyi Li, Wenyou Zhu, and Yongjun Liu* ABSTRACT: ChaP is a non-heme iron-dependent dioxygenase belonging to the vicinal oxygen chelate (VOC) enzyme super- family that catalyzes the ﬁnal α-pyrone ring formation in the to other common biosynthesis of chartreusin. dioxygenases, for example, 2,3-catechol dioxygenase which uses the dioxygen molecule as the oxidant, ChaP requires the ﬂavin- 2−) as the equivalent. Previous experiments activated oxygen (O2 showed that the ChaP-catalyzed ring rearrangement contains two successive C−C bond cleavages and one lactonization; however, the detailed reaction mechanism is unknown. In this work, on the basis of the recently obtained crystal structure of ChaP, the computational model was constructed and the catalytic mechanism of ChaP was explored by performing quantum mechanical/molecular mechanical (QM/MM) calculations. Our calculation results reveal that ChaP uses the proximal oxygen in iron-coordinated HOO− to attack the carbonyl carbon of the substrate, whereas the 2− is unlikely. In the ﬁrst stage previous proposal that Asp49 acts as a base to deprotonate the iron-coordinated HOO− to generate O2 reaction, owing to the coordination of the substrate with iron, the substrate is activated by accepting an electron from iron and the resulting oxy-radical intermediate formed by O−O cleavage can easily trigger the ring rearrangement. In the ﬁnal decarboxylation, the phenolic anion of the substrate cooperatively accepts the proton of iron-coordinated HOO− to facilitate the attack of the distal oxygen, and the proton-coupled electron transfer (PCET) from the substrate to the FeIVO plays a key role for the decarboxylation. These ﬁndings may provide useful information for understanding the ChaP-catalyzed oxidative rearrangement and other ﬂavin- dependent non-heme dioxygenases.

INTRODUCTION The natural product chartreusin was ﬁrst isolated from in 1953 during the Streptomyces chartreusis by Leach et al. screening of antibacterial agents against Mycobacterium tuber- culosis.1 Chartreusin is composed of fucose, digitalose, and an unusual bislactone aglycone.2 Further studies revealed that chartreusin binds to DNA and induces the apoptosis of tumor cells,3 showing promising anticancer activity in a phase II clinical study. In 2005, a revised biosynthetic pathway of chartreusin was proposed, which involves an oxidative rearrangement.4 It was demonstrated that the basic carbon skeleton of chartreusin is constructed from 10 malonyl-CoA’s and an S-adenosyl methionine catalyzed by the type II polyketide synthase (PKS) and the oxidative rearrangement of regular polyketide to the pentacyclic aromatic bislactone chartarin is catalyzed by some cha tailoring enzymes, including the unusual ring-cleaving oxido reductases and a putative 2- glycosyl transferase, among which a rather small dioxygenase ChaP was proposed to be responsible for the ﬁnal unprecedent oxidative rearrangement, as shown in Scheme 1a. The mechanism of biological oxygen activation has been of focus for biochemists in the past decades.5 ChaP belongs to non-heme iron-dependent oxygenases which have been proven to be eﬀective and essential catalysts for nature to activate dioxygen in the synthesis of diversiﬁed biomolecules.6 Among the structurally characterized mononuclear non-heme iron oxygenases, a common structural motif of 2-His-1-carboxylate triad serves as a versatile platform for dioxygen facial activation.7 Generally, four typical non-heme oxygenases with common but ﬂexible mechanisms for oxygen activation have been identiﬁed, including extradiol dioxygenases, α-ketoacid dependent enzymes, Rieske dioxygenases, and pterin-depend- ent hydroxylases.8 Dioxygen is usually activated by direct coordination to the iron, and distinct oxidizing species and https://dx.doi.org/10.1021/acs.inorgchem.0c01706 Inorg. a two-electron reduction in extradiol dioxygenases,10 α- ketoacid dependent enzymes,11 and pterin-dependent hydrox- ylases,12 whereas in the case of Rieske dioxygenases13 an ironIII-hydroperoxy intermediate (Scheme 2b) or a putative HO−FeVO intermediate (Scheme 2c) was suggested as the reactive species. The cleavage of the O−O bond tends to two diﬀerent fates:8b a typical high-spin iron-oxo species FeIVO (Scheme 2d) that has been characterized in many α-KG dependent enzymes14 or pterin-dependent hydroxylases,15 and the Fe−OH complex such as in extradiol dioxygenases10 (Scheme 2e). Several typical oxidative species are summarized in Scheme 2. The mechanism for the biosynthesis of chartreusin remains a long-standing mystery. It was not until 2018 that the Ge group determined the crystal structure of ChaP and investigated the unusual oxidative rearrangement using docking, site-directed mutagenesis, and series of biochemical characterizations.16 The crystal structure of ChaP shows a 2-His-1-carboxylate facial triad of the iron-binding site (Figure S1a). In addition, there exists a narrow channel between Tyr125 and Arg102, allowing the polycyclic substrate to enter into the active site and to coordinate with iron ion. Moreover, no activity was observed if the substrate was incubated only with ChaP and without the addition of FAD, NADH, and ﬂavin reductase.16 Thus, according to the non-heme iron-dependent catechol 2,3-

dioxygenases10 that catalyze the oxidative cleavage of C−C bond using O2 as the oxidant and the substrate o- benzoquinone of ChaP that has two electrons less than the Ge group16 ﬁrst proposed the possible catechol, mechanism of ChaP and ﬁnally demonstrated that the ChaP- catalyzed oxidative rearrangement requires the ﬂavin reductase (Fre) to provide the 4a-ﬂavin hydroperoxide (Fl-4a-OOH) as 2− equivalent. Considering the similarity of the reactions the O2 catalyzed by ChaP and extradiol dioxygenases (Scheme 1), the catalysis of ChaP was proposed to follow the “2,3-catechol dioxygenase”-like pathway.16 ChaP is the ﬁrst example of dioxygenases that uses the ﬂavin-activated oxygen as an oxidant, which also represents a new class in the vicinal oxygen chelate (VOC) enzyme superfamily.16 So far, many experimental and computational works6 have given a detailed interpretation of dioxygen activation by non- heme iron enzymes; however, the study regarding catalysis of the non-heme iron-activated hydroperoxide anion (HOO−) is still very limited. In the previous study,16 a seven-membered lactone intermediate has been conﬁrmed as an on-pathway intermediate. The neighboring Asp49 stabilizes the iron- coordinated HOO− by forming a hydrogen bond and initiates the reaction through deprotonation, whose role is similar to that of histidine in extradiol dioxygenases.10,17 In addition, in the second C−C cleavage of removing the carboxyl group, another ﬂavin-activated HOO− is required to rebound to FeII. In general, open questions still remain. For example, how the iron-coordinated HOO− initiates the reaction and how it catalyzes the ring rearrangement and decarboxylation by two successive C−C bond cleavage processes are unclear. Herein, we performed quantum mechanical/molecular mechanical (QM/MM) calculations to elucidate the catalysis of the ChaP enzyme.

2.1. Molecular Dynamics (MD) Simulations. In the X-ray structure of ChaP (PDB code: 6A4Z), two solvent molecules (W1 and W2 in Figure S1a) and Tyr125 occupied the three available coordination sites besides the 2-His-1-carboxylate facial triad. Since the crystal of ChaP lacks the substrate, the Ge group docked the substrate and hydroperoxide anion (HOO−) into the active site by using the Induced Fit Docking workﬂow.16 The docking poses were selected using the BphC−substrate−NO complex (PDB: 1KW8) as reference, and its reasonability has been analyzed in detail.16 In this study, we directly used the docking result of Ge et al. to construct the computational model. Compared with the crystal, in the docked structure, four residues (Gln91, Tyr92, Arg102, and Tyr125) have slightly changed their conformations owing to the access of the substrate (Figure S2). By these minor checking the substrate binding pocket of ChaP, conformational changes are reasonable, because the space between Tyr125 and Arg102 is the only suitable position to accommodate the substrate.16 Moreover, the substrate pentacyclic o-benzoquinone coordinates with FeII two o- in bidentate form through its benzoquinone groups, which is similar to that of the substrate in catechol 2,3-dioxygenases. To construct for MD simulations, the protonation states of all titratable residues were assigned according to their pKa values calculated by the PROPKA program18 in combination with visual inspections with the VMD software.19 According to the experimental pH of 6.0, all aspartic acid and glutamic acid residues were set to be deprotonated and all arginine and lysine residues were protonated. All histidine residues were set to singly protonated states, among which His7 and His63 were protonated at δ positions. The missing H atoms of the crystal structure of ChaP were added by the HBUILD in the CHARMM package.20 Then, the system was solvated into a water sphere with a

https://dx.doi.org/10.1021/acs.inorgchem.0c01706 Inorg. Chem. XXXX, XXX, XXX−XXX radius of 36 Å using the TIP3P model.21 To neutralize the system, 20 Na+ ions were randomly added into the system. Before the MD simulations, a series of energy minimizations were conducted to the prepared system. Subsequently, the system was subjected to a heating process from 0 to 298.15 K for 200 ps with a time step of 1 fs and then an equilibration for 200 ps at 298.15 K with a time step of 1 fs. To equilibrate the whole solvated model, we ﬁrst performed 20 ns MD simulations using the CHARMM22/CMAP all atom force ﬁeld22 and then performed another 10 ns for comparison. During the MD simulations, to avoid the collapse of the active site, the iron atom and its coordinated atoms were kept frozen, which is a common strategy for non-heme dioxygenases.23 The system was basically equilibrated after 5 ns, which could be inferred from Figure S3 which shows the change of root-mean-square deviation (RMSD) of the backbone atoms of the protein during MD simulations. A superposition of three snapshots from the MD trajectories at 20, 25, and 30 ns is shown in Figure S4. In general, three structures show high consistency. The snapshot at 20 ns was extracted for our subsequent QM/MM calculations. 2.2. QM/MM Calculations. All QM/MM calculations were carried out using the ChemShell program,24 which combines the Turbomole program25 for the QM region and the DL_POLY program26 for the MM region. The whole system was divided into a QM region and a MM region. The QM region (Scheme 3) contains Scheme 3. QM Region Selected for the QM/MM Calculations

the substrate pentacyclic o-benzoquinone, iron, and its coordinated residues (His7, His63, and Glu119) as well as the HOO− group. Besides, the deprotonated residue Asp49 may act as a catalytic acid/ base, and the nearby residues (Phe37, Gln91, Arg102, and Tyr109) form strong interactions with the substrate and Glu119; therefore, they were also included in the QM region. The remaining atoms were put into the MM part. To consider the polarizing eﬀect of the MM region on the QM region, the electronic embedding scheme27 was applied. No electrostatic cutoﬀ was introduced for MM/MM and QM/MM interactions. The boundary between the QM region and the MM region was treated with the hydrogen linked atoms with the charge shift model.28 During QM/MM calculations, all atoms within 16 Å of the iron atom were deﬁned as the active region which was fully optimized, whereas the rest of the MM region was kept frozen. The QM region was treated by the unrestricted hybrid UB3LYP density functional

For the ChaP-catalyzed system, both substrates o-benzoquinone and hydroperoxide anion (HOO−) coordinate with the iron ion and there must be an electron transfer between substrates and iron. To determine the reactant state of the reactive center, we ﬁrst optimized the whole system at the close-shell singlet (cssR), open-shell singlet (1R), triplet, quintet, and septet states. The results are displayed in Figure 1. Another triplet state (3′R) was obtained by ﬂipping a β-electron of 1R to an α- electron in the iron center. According to the previously proposed mechanism,16 we assigned the peroxide anion as protonated (HOO−) and Asp49 as deprotonated. Our calculation results show that the septet is the ground state and the quintet state is 10.0 kcal/mol higher than the septet state. In addition, the open-shell singlet (1R) and one triplet state (3R) have comparable relative energies as the quintet state, and the closed-shell singlet (cssR) has the highest relative energy (see Figure 1). 3.2. Formation of Oxy-Radical Intermediate. Most of non-heme dioxygenases10,39 initiate the catalytic reaction by attack of iron-coordinated dioxygen on the substrate; however, for ChaP, the binding nature and reactivity of the oxidant have been changed, and whether the proximal oxygen or distal oxygen attacks the carbonyl carbon of the substrate is unknown. Therefore, we designed three possible pathways to explore the formation of the key oxy-radical intermediate, which diﬀer from the attack mode of iron-coordinated oxygen and the proton transfer mode of HOO− (Scheme 4). In the previous experimental study,16 it was proposed that the neighboring Asp49 stabilizes HOO− by forming a hydrogen bond and initiates the reaction through deprotona- tion. Thus, we ﬁrst explored the possibility of proton transfer from HOO− to Asp49 to generate the Fe-coordinated OO− in Scheme 4). However, neither the stepwise proton (Ra transfer nor the concerted pathway where the proton abstraction is accompanied by a radical attack was recognized by a reasonable transition state. We attribute it to the weaker alkalinity of the deprotonated Asp49 than the iron-coordinated 2−. The scanned energy proﬁle for the proton transfer from O2 HOO− to Asp49 is shown in Figure S7. One can see that the scanned energy continuously increased until Asp49 was repelled to a distance to form a stable intermediate, i.e., only when the distance between the HOO− and the carboxyl group of Asp49 is long enough can the proton transfer to Asp49. However, in 5R, the distance between the carboxyl oxygen and the proton in HOO− is only 1.81 Å, which excludes the possibility of the proton transfer. The calculated spin density of Fe has decreased to 2.77 from 3.70, and that of O3 increases to 0.57 (Table S2). Although path-a only corresponds to an overall barrier of 13.1 kcal/mol at the quintet state, considering the proton transfer from the HOO− to Asp49 is actually infeasible, path-a should be an unlikely pathway. We have also calculated path-a at the triplet state (Figure S9), and the results show that the triplet state corresponds to a higher energy surface than the quintet state.

Then, we explored the pathway that the proximal oxygen of the iron-coordinated superoxide radical directly attacks the carbonyl carbon of substrate (path-b in Scheme 4). According to our calculations, the proximal oxygen attacks the carbonyl C2 of the substrate and simultaneously the Fe−O coordinate bond breaks to aﬀord IM1b, which corresponds to a barrier of 14.7 kcal/mol (Figure 5). The optimized structures are shown in Figure S10. In IM1b, the OOH group has covalently bonded to the substrate. To assist the cleavage of the O−O bond in IM1b, the distal O3 atom should recoordinate to iron and a hydroxyl rotation is required (step from 5IM1b to 5IM2b in Figure S10). Figure 5 shows that this rotation corresponds to a barrier of 3.6 kcal/mol. After rotation of the hydroxyl group, the lone electron pair on the O3 atom faces toward iron, facilitating the O−O cleavage by the coordination of the hydroxyl group with iron. IM2b cleaves its O−O bond with a barrier of 12.9 kcal/mol, and the break of the O−O bond is in concert with the coordination of the hydroxyl group with iron. Figure 5 shows that the attack on the carbonyl C2 atom by the proximal oxygen of superoxide is the rate-limiting step. We also calculated path-b at the septet state, which corresponds to a high energy barrier of 38.8 kcal/mol (Figure S11). Therefore, the septet state of the reactant may represent an unreactive state. Using the septet state reactant as the reference, the overall energy barrier should increase by about 10 kcal/mol. However, considering the geometrical structures of the quintet and septet states are very similar, the system crossing of the reactant from the septet to the quintet state should be quite easy.

Another possible pathway (path-c) was also considered. In this pathway, the attack of the distal oxygen in Fe-OOH on the carbonyl C2 is in concert with the O−O bond cleavage, generating FeIVO and the tetrahedral intermediate 5IM1c. This step corresponds to a barrier of 19.3 kcal/mol on the quintet surface, which is about 5 kcal/mol higher than that in path-b. The optimized structures are shown in Figure S12. In ﬁrst the following reaction, the hydroxyl group at C2 of 5IM1c then the FeIVO undergoes a rotation to form 5IM2c, abstracts a hydrogen atom from the hydroxyl group. Our calculations reveal that although the hydroxyl rotation step is very easy, the hydrogen abstraction corresponds to a barrier of 16.1 kcal/mol at the quintet state. Moreover, the 5IM2c is more stable than 5IM3c, suggesting this hydrogen abstraction to be energetically unfavorable. To test the reactivity of the septet reactant, path-c was also calculated and the energy proﬁle is displayed in Figure S13. Thus, path-c is also an unfavorable pathway. 3.3. Oxidative Rearrangement. After the formation of the oxy-radical intermediate, the highly reactive oxygen radical triggers the intramolecular insertion via an epoxide ring intermediate (IM4), forming a seven-membered ring lactone intermediate (IM5 in Scheme 5), then the Fe−OH complex carries out the hydroxylation reaction resulting in the ring rearrangement. The optimized structures of the involved species in the oxidative rearrangement are shown in Figure S14, and the energy proﬁle is displayed in Figure 6. We found Figure 6. Energy proﬁle for the oxidative rearrangement process from IM3b to IM7 at the quintet state. that IM3 (IM3b was used as the starting structure) ﬁrst forms an epoxide ring intermediate (IM4), which is a very shallow minimum and can easily cleave its C2−C3 bond to form the seven-membered ring intermediate IM5. From IM4 to IM5, an electron transfers from the substrate to the iron and the FeIII is reduced to FeII. The relevant spin densities are summarized in Table S3.

Similar to the case of other extradiol dioxygenases,10,39 the Fe-bound hydroxyl group attacks the C2 atom of the substrate to aﬀord a tetrahedral intermediate, which has been identiﬁed to be quite easy. In IM5, the C2 atom corresponds to a shorter distance from the Fe-bound hydroxyl group and bears more spin densities than the C1 atom; thus, the iron-coordinated hydroxyl group prefers to rebound to the carbonyl C2 atom to generate IM6, which corresponds to a barrier of 4.6 kcal/mol. In IM6, the tetrahedral C2 intermediate is very unstable and can easily isomerize to IM7. The rearrangement from IM6 to IM7 is a complex process, in which the C2−O3 bond cleaves and the O3−C1 bond forms and simultaneously a proton transfers to the deprotonated Asp49. This ring contraction step corresponds to a barrier of 7.0 kcal/mol. 3.4. Decarboxylation Reaction. According to the previously proposed mechanism,16 the second hydroperoxide anion (HOO−) would enter into the active site to coordinate with FeII and initiate the subsequent decarboxylation reaction. Based on the structure of IM7, we constructed the computa- tional model by introducing another iron-coordinated HOO−. The optimized structures (named as IM8) at the triplet and quintet states are shown in Figure 7. We found that the Figure 7. Optimized structure of IM8 at the triplet and quintet states. We have conducted QM/MM calculations to elucidate a plausible catalytic mechanism of the dioxygenase ChaP. On the basis of our calculations, the most possible reaction pathway for the oxidative rearrangement has been recognized, as shown in Scheme 6. Since ChaP uses the ﬂavin-activated oxygen 2−) as the equivalent, the iron-coordinated HOO− shows (O2 diﬀerent reactivity and reaction mode with the common dioxygenases such as 2,3-catechol dioxygenase that employs Fe−O2 as the active species. On the one hand, owing to the diﬀerent electronic structures of iron-coordinated oxidants (HOO− and O2) and the substrates, the iron-coordinated HOO− shows a poor radical characteristic compared with the iron-coordinated dioxygen. If the iron-coordinated HOO− can be deprotonated by the nearby residue, as was proposed in the 2− was calculated to previous study,16 the iron-coordinated O2 be highly active and can easily trigger the oxidative rearrangement. However, no surrounding residue can act as the catalytic base to extract the proton from the Fe- coordinated HOO−. Thus, the iron-coordinated HOO− is proposed to be the active species to directly initiate the the oxidative rearrangement. Our calculations reveal proximal oxygen in iron-coordinated HOO− triggers the radical attack on the substrate carbonyl carbon to initiate the reaction. On the other hand, ChaP requires the second ﬂavin- activated HOO− to catalyze the decarboxylation reaction. During the decarboxylation, the substrate phenolic hydroxyl anion acts as the catalytic base to abstract the proton of the iron-coordinated HOO−, facilitating the attack of Fe−O2 2− on the carbonyl carbon. Further, the decarboxylation is assisted by two PCET steps. The whole reaction was calculated to proceed on the quintet surface. These ﬁndings may provide useful information for understanding the catalysis of dioxygenase ChaP and other related enzymes belonging to the VOC family in engineering and and may also have implications modiﬁcation for relevant enzymes.
